<li id="cite_note-24"><b><a href="#cite_ref-24" title="">^</a></b> compare: Guide de Ruggeiro: The History of European Liberalism, Bacon press, 1954, page 379</li>
<li id="cite_note-25"><b><a href="#cite_ref-25" title="">^</a></b> See for more information the Liberale und radikale Parteien in Klaus von Beyme: Parteien in westlichen Demokratien, München, 1982</li>
<li id="cite_note-26"><b><a href="#cite_ref-26" title="">^</a></b> Compare page 255 and further in the Guide to the Political Parties of South America (Pelican Books, 1973</li>
<li id="cite_note-27"><b><a href="#cite_ref-27" title="">^</a></b> See page 1 and further of A sense of liberty, by Julie Smith, published by the Liberal International in 1997.</li>
<li id="cite_note-28"><b><a href="#cite_ref-28" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.mackinac.org/archives/1998/sp1998-01.pdf" class="external free" title="http://www.mackinac.org/archives/1998/sp1998-01.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://www.mackinac.org/archives/1998/sp1998-01.pdf</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-29"><b><a href="#cite_ref-29" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/economics/laureates/1974/press.html" class="external free" title="http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/economics/laureates/1974/press.html" rel="nofollow">http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/economics/laureates/1974/press.html</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-30"><b><a href="#cite_ref-30" title="">^</a></b> See for example <a href="/wiki/Arthur_Schlesinger,_Jr." title="Arthur Schlesinger, Jr." class="mw-redirect">Arthur Schlesinger, Jr.</a> in 1962: <i>Liberalism in the American usage has little in common with the word as used in the politics of any European country, save possibly Britain</i> in <a href="http://www.writing.upenn.edu/~afilreis/50s/schleslib.html" class="external text" title="http://www.writing.upenn.edu/~afilreis/50s/schleslib.html" rel="nofollow">Liberalism in America: A Note for Europeans</a> from <i>The Politics of Hope</i>, Riverside Press, Boston. See for a similar view Jamie F. Metzl: <i>In the same "Liberalism" as the term is used in America today is not used in the "older, European sense,</i> but <i>has come to mean something quite different, namely policies upholding the modern welfare state</i> in <a href="http://www.theihs.org/pdf/materials/513.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.theihs.org/pdf/materials/513.pdf" rel="nofollow"><i>The Rise of Illiberal Democracy</i></a> by <a href="/wiki/Fareed_Zakaria" title="Fareed Zakaria">Fareed Zakaria</a>, Foreign Affairs, November/December, 1997, Vol 76, No. 6</li>
<li id="cite_note-31"><b><a href="#cite_ref-31" title="">^</a></b> <i><a href="/wiki/The_Future_of_Freedom" title="The Future of Freedom">The Future of Freedom</a>: Illiberal Democracy at Home and Abroad</i>, <a href="/wiki/Fareed_Zakaria" title="Fareed Zakaria">Fareed Zakaria</a>, (W.W. Norton &amp; Company; 2003) <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0393047644" class="internal">ISBN 0-393-04764-4</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-32"><b><a href="#cite_ref-32" title="">^</a></b> See for example the <a href="http://www.liberal-international.org/editorial.asp?ia_id=537" class="external text" title="http://www.liberal-international.org/editorial.asp?ia_id=537" rel="nofollow">Oxford Manifesto 1997</a> of the Liberal International.</li>
<li id="cite_note-33"><b><a href="#cite_ref-33" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.liberal-international.org/editorial.asp?ia_id=535" class="external text" title="http://www.liberal-international.org/editorial.asp?ia_id=535" rel="nofollow">Oxford Manifesto</a>, 1947</li>
<li id="cite_note-34"><b><a href="#cite_ref-34" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.liberal-international.org/editorial.asp?ia_id=508" class="external text" title="http://www.liberal-international.org/editorial.asp?ia_id=508" rel="nofollow">Liberal International &gt; The International</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-35"><b><a href="#cite_ref-35" title="">^</a></b> “Herzlichen Glückwunsch, Neoliberalismus!” from Romanus Otte in <a href="/wiki/Die_Welt" title="Die Welt">Die Welt</a> (<a href="http://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&amp;sl=de&amp;u=http://www.welt.de/welt_print/article2342273/Herzlichen-Glueckwunsch-Neoliberalismus.html&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=translate&amp;resnum=8&amp;ct=result&amp;prev=/search%3Fq%3D%2522Colloque%2BWalter%2BLippmann%2522%2B%2522Alexander%2BR%25C3%25BCstow%2522%2Bneoliberalism%26start%3D10%26hl%3Den%26sa%3DN" class="external text" title="http://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&amp;sl=de&amp;u=http://www.welt.de/welt_print/article2342273/Herzlichen-Glueckwunsch-Neoliberalismus.html&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=translate&amp;resnum=8&amp;ct=result&amp;prev=/search%3Fq%3D%2522Colloque%2BWalter%2BLippmann%2522%2B%2522Alexander%2BR%25C3%25BCstow%2522%2Bneoliberalism%26start%3D10%26hl%3Den%26sa%3DN" rel="nofollow">Google translation</a>)</li>
<li id="cite_note-fraser-36">^ <a href="#cite_ref-fraser_36-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-fraser_36-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> Economic Freedom of the World 2005, Fraser Institute</li>
<li id="cite_note-37"><b><a href="#cite_ref-37" title="">^</a></b> Francis Parker Yockey, "Imperium: The Philosophy of History and Politics", 1948, p. 207</li>
